result.execSummary:
The defendant Michelle L Ansay was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: If probation is revoked or will discharge with outstanding financial obligations due, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due.

Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment or schooling or combination thereof to equal full time.  

Defendant shall partake in vocational training as requested by the agent.

Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.

Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol or controlled substance without a valid prescription and then taken as prescribed.

Defendant shall not possess any drug paraphernalia.

Defendant shall not associate with or have any contact with any drug dealers or users.

Defendant shall not be present where illegal drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged or distributed.

Defendant shall have no contact with Jacon M. or After Hours Lingerie and Gifts.

Contact with David M. as per the agent.

Defendant shall participate in all counseling and/or treatment programs directed by the probation agent and comply with recommendations.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample.

Defendant shall submit to random drug screens.

Defendant shall make monthly payments toward court obligations and pay any supervision fees as determined by the Department of Corrections.

Defendant shall advise the agent of prescription changes within 48 hours of the change.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA assessment and comply with treatment recommendations.
